AmiTCP_NG -- an open TCP/IP stack for AmigaOS
=============================================

AmiTCP_NG is a free, open-source TCP/IP stack for 68k AmigaOS (2.04 and later).
It provides a drop-in "bsdsocket.library" -- the standard Amiga networking API --
so existing Amiga network software just works, with no time limit.

It is a modern-toolchain revival of AmiTCP/IP 3.0b2, and a 100% drop-in
replacement for Olaf Barthel's Roadshow: it speaks the same bsdsocket.library
API, uses the same configuration files, and ships the same command set, so
Roadshow's own tools and front-ends (Roadie, NetMon) drive it unchanged.

The Roadshow-compatible parts are a clean-room re-implementation, written from
scratch using the open Roadshow SDK only as a reference -- no Roadshow code is
included. With thanks to Olaf Barthel for making that SDK available.

Copyright (C) 2026 Andy Taylor (MW0MWZ). Released under the GNU GPL v2 (see the
COPYING file). Portions derive from AmiTCP/IP 3.0b2 (AmiTCP/IP Group) and the
4.4BSD-Lite networking code (see COPYRIGHTS).


Requirements
------------

  * AmigaOS 2.04 or later, any 68000 (or better) Amiga.
  * A SANA-II network device driver for your card (e.g. a2065.device for the
    Commodore A2065, or your card's driver), installed in DEVS:Networks/.


Installing
----------

Double-click "Install-AmiTCP_NG" (or run it with the Installer tool).

How much the installer asks depends on the USER LEVEL you pick in the Installer's
opening dialog (the standard Amiga Novice / Intermediate / Expert choice):

  * NOVICE -- the installer asks NOTHING and takes every default. It installs the
    "AmiTCP" drawer to "SYS:Programs/AmiTCP" (or "SYS:AmiTCP" if you have no
    Programs drawer), and if it finds an existing TCP/IP stack it automatically
    upgrades it (see UPGRADE below). This is the "just install it" path.

  * INTERMEDIATE / EXPERT -- unlocks the extra choices:
      - which action to perform:
          Install ..... put AmiTCP_NG on this machine.
          Uninstall ... roll back a previous AmiTCP_NG install.
          Preview ..... show exactly what an install would do, changing nothing.
        (Uninstall / roll back is ONLY offered above Novice level.)
      - WHERE the "AmiTCP" drawer (its configuration and host database) is
        created -- any volume or drawer; the default is still
        "SYS:Programs/AmiTCP" (or "SYS:AmiTCP" with no Programs drawer).

Either way the installer sets up an "AmiTCP:" assign to wherever the drawer ends
up. The install METHOD is chosen automatically from what is already present, so
it cannot do the wrong thing:

  * UPGRADE (an existing TCP/IP stack was detected -- a "bsdsocket.library", an
    "AddNetInterface" command, a "DEVS:NetInterfaces" drawer or an
    "S:Network-Startup", for example a Roadshow install). AmiTCP_NG backs up your
    original "LIBS:bsdsocket.library" as "LIBS:bsdsocket.library.orig" and replaces
    it, and installs its own network commands (Online, Offline, AddNetInterface,
    ShowNetStatus, ...) over the existing ones, backing up each original as
    "C:<name>.orig". Your interface configuration in "DEVS:NetInterfaces" is left
    untouched and now drives AmiTCP_NG, with no time limit. Replacing the commands
    is deliberate: the previous stack's own tools (e.g. Roadshow's AddNetInterface)
    do not drive AmiTCP_NG's library correctly, so AmiTCP_NG supplies matching
    commands of its own. (Stack-specific extras of the previous stack, such as
    Roadshow's PPP/PPPoE drivers or its IP-filter firewall, are not provided by
    AmiTCP_NG.)

  * FULL INSTALL (no stack was detected). AmiTCP_NG installs the library AND its
    own complete set of Roadshow-compatible commands into C: (Online, Offline,
    AddNetInterface, ConfigureNetInterface, AddNetRoute, DeleteNetRoute,
    RemoveNetInterface, NetShutdown, GetNetStatus, ShowNetStatus, ping), an
    "S:Network-Startup" script, example interface configurations in
    "SYS:Storage/NetInterfaces", and a line in "S:User-Startup" to bring the
    network up at boot.

Reboot when the installer finishes.


Configuring an interface (full install)
---------------------------------------

1. Copy an example from "SYS:Storage/NetInterfaces" into "DEVS:NetInterfaces",
   renaming it to whatever you want the interface to be called, e.g. "eth0".

2. Edit it for your hardware. The key settings are:

       device=a2065.device      ; your card's SANA-II driver
       unit=0                    ; device unit (usually 0)
       configure=dhcp            ; get address/DNS automatically, OR omit this
                                 ; and set a static address instead:
       ; address=192.168.0.10
       ; netmask=255.255.255.0
       ; gateway=192.168.0.1

3. Reboot, or bring it up now from a Shell -- the interface name is enough (it is
   looked up in DEVS:NetInterfaces, exactly like Roadshow); a full path also works:

       AddNetInterface eth0

These are the same configuration files Roadshow uses, so existing Roadshow
interface configurations work unchanged.


Uninstalling / rolling back
---------------------------

Run "Install-AmiTCP_NG" again, pick the INTERMEDIATE or EXPERT user level at the
start (Uninstall is not offered at Novice level), and choose "Uninstall". It
automatically does the right thing:

  * If you had upgraded over an existing stack, your backed-up library
    ("LIBS:bsdsocket.library.orig") and every backed-up command ("C:<name>.orig")
    are restored, putting your previous stack back exactly as it was.

  * If it was a full install, the AmiTCP_NG library and every command it
    installed are removed.

Either way the "AmiTCP:" assign and the AmiTCP_NG lines in "S:User-Startup" are
removed. Your "AmiTCP" drawer and your "DEVS:NetInterfaces" configuration are
left in place (delete them by hand if you no longer want them). Reboot to finish.


